13 SECTION 4. TRANSPARENCY AND LEGISLATIVE OVERSIGHT OF ICOM NEGOTIA-
14 TIONS. Idaho State University, under the oversight of the State Board of
15 Education and the Legislature, shall lead any negotiations that may result
16 in the acquisition or proposed acquisition of the Idaho College of Osteo-
17 pathic Medicine (ICOM). Idaho State University and the Office of the State
18 Board of Education shall provide information regarding the acquisition or
19 proposed acquisition of ICOM at the request of the Legislative Services
20 Office. Requested information may include but is not limited to current or
21 historical financial data, operational data, correspondences, draft agree-
22 ments, and briefing materials. Except as otherwise required by law, no state
23 officer, board member, or employee may enter into a non-disclosure agreement
24 or any contract that conflicts with this section.
25 SECTION 5. PRIORITIZING WATER RESEARCH IN IDAHO HIGHER EDUCATION. Of
26 the funds appropriated in Section 1 of this act for Systemwide Program,
27 $1,000,000 shall be used for the Idaho Water Resources Research Institute
28 (IWRRI). Expenditure of these funds shall be at the direction of the IWRRI
29 Executive Committee consistent with the Institute's research priorities.
30 IWRRI shall encourage rigorous, actionable water research at all of Idaho's
31 public institutions of higher learning and shall fund research projects
32 accordingly. The IWRRI Director shall submit an interim report to the Joint
33 Finance-Appropriations Committee by December 1, 2025, and an end-of-fiscal
34 year report by June 30, 2026 on the expenditure of these funds. The format
35 and content of this report will be determined in consultation with the Budget
36 and Policy Analysis Division of the Legislative Services Office.
37 SECTION 6. TRANSITIONING TO OUTCOMES-BASED FUNDING IN HIGHER EDU-
38 CATION. The Office of the State Board of Education shall develop an out-
39 comes-based funding model to replace the Enrollment Workload Adjustment
40 for Idaho's college and universities. The Office of the State Board shall
41 deliver a written proposal to the Joint Finance-Appropriations Committee by
42 December 31, 2025, with a plan for implementation of the new funding model
43 in fiscal year 2028 or earlier. The Office of the State Board of Education
44 shall provide written reports to the Joint Finance-Appropriations Committee
45 on a quarterly basis detailing progress towards the outcomes-based funding

4
1 model. The format and content of this report will be determined in con-
2 sultation with the Budget and Policy Analysis Division of the Legislative
3 Services Office.
4 SECTION 7. DEI AUDITS. The Legislative Audits Division of the Legisla-
5 tive Services Office will audit Boise State University, Idaho State Univer-
6 sity, Lewis-Clark State College, and the University of Idaho for compliance
7 with those portions of Idaho Code prohibiting or relating to diversity, eq-
8 uity, and inclusion in higher education. Legislative Audits will bill the
9 respective institutions for these audits. The Legislative Audits Division
10 will report its findings to the Joint Finance-Appropriations Committee by
11 December 1, 2025.
12 SECTION 8. REDUCTIONS IN APPROPRIATION. Of the reductions included in
13 Section 2 of this act for Boise State University and the University of Idaho,
14 amounts are reduced on a onetime basis, and the institutions are permitted
15 to restore such reductions to the base appropriation in the following year's
16 budget submission required by Section 67-3502, Idaho Code.
17 SECTION 9. CONDITIONS, LIMITATIONS, AND RESTRICTIONS. Appropriations
18 made pursuant to this act are subject to the conditions, limitations, and re-
19 strictions specified in this act.
20 SECTION 10. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
21 declared to exist, this act shall be in full force and effect on and after
22 July 1, 2025.

